WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:09.245 --> 00:00:11.370
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR:
I'm Juliet Ehimuan-Chiazor.

00:00:11.370 --> 00:00:14.720
And I feel very
honored and really

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:17.985
delighted to be moderating
this panel of these very

00:00:17.985 --> 00:00:20.096
inspiring women.

00:00:20.096 --> 00:00:26.014
I'm going to start by
introducing them very briefly.

00:00:26.014 --> 00:00:27.810
You are very familiar
with who they are.

00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:30.300
So I'll start to
my immediate left.

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:32.330
This is Ibukun Awosika.

00:00:32.330 --> 00:00:36.250
She's the first female
Chairman, Board of Directors,

00:00:36.250 --> 00:00:38.116
First Bank of Nigeria Limited.

00:00:38.116 --> 00:00:40.960
She's also the founder and CEO.

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:43.460
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:45.870
We're very proud.

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:50.460
She's also the founder and
CEO of the Chair Centre Group.

00:00:50.460 --> 00:00:53.560
She's a multiple-award-winning
entrepreneur,

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:56.310
and the first
Nigerian recipient of

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:59.940
the prestigious International
Women Entrepreneurial Challenge

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:00.440
Award.

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:08.420
She currently sits
on many boards

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:11.540
and is a co-founder
and past chairperson

00:01:11.540 --> 00:01:15.621
of Women In Business Management
and Public Service, Wimbiz.

00:01:15.621 --> 00:01:18.270
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:21.490
Ibukun, thank you so much
for joining us today.

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:21.990
It

00:01:21.990 --> 00:01:22.860
IBUKUN AWOSIKA:
You're most welcome.

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:24.860
JULIET EHIMUAN CHIAZOR:
We really appreciate it.

00:01:24.860 --> 00:01:26.610
And we have TY Bello.

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:31.060
She is a multifaceted
woman with a few labels--

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:35.380
singer, songwriter,
photographer,

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:37.073
and philanthropist.

00:01:37.073 --> 00:01:38.997
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:42.430
Prior to pursuing
a solo career, she

00:01:42.430 --> 00:01:46.580
was a member of the
defunct gospel band, Kush.

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:48.910
She's also a member of
the Nigerian photography

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:53.270
collective, Depth of Field, and
was the official photographer

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:56.150
of the former
President of Nigeria.

00:01:56.150 --> 00:01:59.250
She's best known for her
award-winning singles,

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:04.410
"Greenland," "Ekundayo", "This
Man," "Freedom," "Funmise,"

00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:10.910
and "The Morning Songbook."

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:12.960
She stages annual
photography exhibition

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:16.240
to raise funds for orphans
across the country.

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:20.700
She's also a director of Link
a Child, an NGO dedicated

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:25.080
to propagating information
on orphanages in Nigeria,

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:27.180
and soliciting sponsorship
on their behalf.

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:28.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:29.690
It's good to have you here, TY.

00:02:29.690 --> 00:02:30.822
TY BELLO: Thank you.

00:02:30.822 --> 00:02:33.030
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR: So
to start the conversation,

00:02:33.030 --> 00:02:34.630
this will be in two parts.

00:02:34.630 --> 00:02:36.500
We're kicking off
with this panel.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:39.580
And we'll have a second session
after the break with Dr. Oby

00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:41.810
Ezekwesili.

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:45.320
So to start off, I'm going to
ask a relatively broad question

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:49.160
for each member of the panel,
starting with Mrs. Awosika.

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:53.410
So when we think about where
we are in our society today,

00:02:53.410 --> 00:02:55.920
we're talking about
smashing the glass ceiling.

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:57.400
Is there still a glass ceiling?

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:59.120
We have made some progress.

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:01.840
In you opinion, is there
still a glass ceiling?

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:04.700
And what has been
your experience

00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:08.360
around taking decisions to
help you smash or overcome

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:11.015
the glass ceiling?

00:03:11.015 --> 00:03:15.265
IBUKUN AWOSIKA: OK, this glass
ceiling that won't go away.

00:03:15.265 --> 00:03:18.660
I actually think that the
issue of the glass ceiling

00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:22.370
is different for every
woman, and is also different

00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:27.250
depending on where you are in
your career or your business

00:03:27.250 --> 00:03:28.580
life.

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:31.160
It's different in
Nigeria, putting it

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.740
in context is
different depending

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:36.360
on what part of the country
you come from as well.

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:38.670
Because there are
different levels

00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:43.850
that women are at, in terms
of having opportunities,

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:46.430
depending on what part of
the country you come from.

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:50.390
But I think that collectively,
when we look at it,

00:03:50.390 --> 00:03:52.730
no matter what part of
the country you come from,

00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:55.520
we have moved quite
a distance in terms

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:58.560
of the kind of opportunities
that women have.

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:05.430
But that's also a
function of social class.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:06.940
Because that's another thing.

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:11.000
The average middle-class
to upper-class family

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.910
doesn't segregate between who
goes to school, whether it's

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:15.960
the male or the female child.

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:21.440
And the south, especially the
southwestern part of Nigeria,

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:25.320
would have every child from
middle class to upper class,

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:27.850
averagely have a
university education

00:04:27.850 --> 00:04:32.270
and at least attempt to build
a career, one way or the other.

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:34.020
Now, there are other
factors that are then

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.020
beginning to come to play.

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:38.810
Because I think at
the starting point,

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:41.713
male and female start off
basically, equal footing.

00:04:41.713 --> 00:04:42.400
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR:
Little things, [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:43.240
IBUKUN AWOSIKA: Yes.

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:46.510
But along the
path, other factors

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:51.210
that are not even as traditional
as we think begin to show up.

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:55.140
So now you've married a guy
who has his own insecurities.

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:57.180
And because of his
insecurities, he

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:00.180
would like a woman that he
can keep at home and control.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:02.300
So that's not a societal factor.

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:04.520
That's an individual issue.

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:10.220
Or you've married a man who
just doesn't-- in his mind,

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:13.380
his mother was-- well,
is-- a housewife.

00:05:13.380 --> 00:05:15.460
And he grew up with his
mother always been there.

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:18.350
And what he wants is a
wife who is a housewife.

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:23.690
I think the real issue is about
what the women want to do,

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:27.360
in terms of whatever kind
of ceiling is still there.

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:30.580
It's an individual
choice for every woman

00:05:30.580 --> 00:05:33.120
to choose what life
you want to live.

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:34.620
And that comes into play.

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.490
We can play back
to our girl child,

00:05:37.490 --> 00:05:40.550
and start to teach
the girls about having

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:44.500
the ability to make that
choice for themselves.

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:47.190
And that should
start from deciding

00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:50.220
how far they want to go, by
having a sense of who they are.

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:52.880
And at a stage,
deciding who they

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.660
want to marry based on
who they want to be.

00:05:56.660 --> 00:06:00.890
And choosing the spouse is a
key success factor in my books.

00:06:00.890 --> 00:06:02.530
So if you have a
sense of who you

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:05.200
are, you have a sense of
how far you want to go,

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:08.150
when a nice-looking rich
and handsome guy who

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:10.690
wants a housewife comes
calling, you don't even listen.

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:12.765
Because he doesn't fit
where you want to go.

00:06:12.765 --> 00:06:14.890
So it's not a matter of
that he wants to marry you.

00:06:14.890 --> 00:06:17.610
It is a matter of do
you want to marry him?

00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:20.200
Does he fit into the
life you want to live?

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:22.940
Does he fit into the future
you see for yourself?

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:26.250
Now, so as we take some
of the fundamental issues

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:29.082
and we move forward, we
then get into the workplace.

00:06:29.082 --> 00:06:30.540
You get into the
workplace and then

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:34.790
you talk about does the woman
understand that she can't play

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:37.320
the feminine card anymore,
if she really wants

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:39.180
her respect in the workplace.

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:43.150
Does she know all that she's
got to earn a place by making

00:06:43.150 --> 00:06:46.590
sure she's competent, she's
capable, she's equipped,

00:06:46.590 --> 00:06:48.190
and she's ready to play.

00:06:48.190 --> 00:06:50.170
Does she understand
she must have courage.

00:06:50.170 --> 00:06:51.390
She must be focused.

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:53.480
She must able to
challenge status quo,

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:55.850
and fight for herself as well.

00:06:55.850 --> 00:06:58.770
Does she know she
mustn't defer to the male

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:00.150
just because he's male.

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:02.644
As long as they're pairs, and
they have equal opportunity,

00:07:02.644 --> 00:07:04.060
she should fight
for the position.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:07.430
So there are many things
that come into play.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:09.620
Because at the end
of the day, one thing

00:07:09.620 --> 00:07:13.320
I can say in my
experience, is that when

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:15.860
you're good at what
you do, there's

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:18.540
a stage where you
can't be ignored,

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:20.090
whether you're male or female.

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:20.700
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR:
That's true.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:22.300
IBUKUN AWOSIKA: There
is a point where

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:26.650
the competition falls apart,
the gender card falls apart.

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:28.470
Because at the end
of the day, what

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:30.430
is the interest
of the shareholder

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:31.820
or the stakeholders?

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:34.530
They want to succeed at
whatever they want to do.

00:07:34.530 --> 00:07:39.652
And when you're
facing the bare facts,

00:07:39.652 --> 00:07:41.610
you're looking for the
best person for the job.

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:44.060
Now, there's all the issue
of OK, boys club, girls club.

00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:45.000
OK, so?

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:46.500
Boys can network.

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:48.270
Girls can network too.

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:51.920
I actually think girls can
be more powerful networkers.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:53.140
Why?

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:55.960
You can use the
network of your spouse.

00:07:55.960 --> 00:07:57.880
And you can use
your own network.

00:07:57.880 --> 00:07:59.530
And when you use
your network, you

00:07:59.530 --> 00:08:02.470
use the network of your
friends and their spouses.

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:07.430
So you can play from both sides
even more than the guy can.

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:11.780
But your strongest weapon
is really about showing up.

00:08:11.780 --> 00:08:16.010
Because the one thing nobody
can ignore is when you show up.

00:08:16.010 --> 00:08:19.460
When you show up at your
table, and your capacity,

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:21.780
your capability,
your competence,

00:08:21.780 --> 00:08:27.650
your ability is so open
for everybody to see.

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:28.760
You can't be ignored.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:31.250
And that narrows the table.

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:33.720
And there's a point
where again, where I know

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:36.250
there's still a mindset issue
that we're dealing with.

00:08:36.250 --> 00:08:39.210
But like I said, the
factors vary depending

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:40.350
on different circumstances.

00:08:40.350 --> 00:08:42.429
But first, let's deal with us.

00:08:42.429 --> 00:08:45.114
So I think when the girls
have said, OK, you know what?

00:08:45.114 --> 00:08:46.530
We're ready to go
the [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:47.983
We're not making excuses,
saying oh, sorry.

00:08:47.983 --> 00:08:48.482
I'm a girl.

00:08:48.482 --> 00:08:49.770
OK, so I have children.

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:51.032
So I have a husband.

00:08:51.032 --> 00:08:52.490
We work out how to
deal with those.

00:08:52.490 --> 00:08:54.590
And I think a lot of girls
can deal with that now.

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:55.590
We find these solutions.

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:56.730
We're not simple women.

00:08:56.730 --> 00:08:57.690
So we receive help.

00:08:57.690 --> 00:08:58.554
We create help.

00:08:58.554 --> 00:09:00.720
So that as a cook to cook,
what's my responsibility?

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:02.800
There must be food on
the table for my family.

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:04.281
Who cares who cooks the food?

00:09:04.281 --> 00:09:05.530
As long as there's food there.

00:09:05.530 --> 00:09:07.850
So my children must
be taken care of.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:10.520
If I cannot afford to take 20
people to take care of them,

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:12.060
then I make it work.

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:14.230
Then somebody must
do my shopping.

00:09:14.230 --> 00:09:15.320
You don't have to know.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:18.600
I can call [INAUDIBLE],
and get everything

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:21.550
delivered into my kitchen.

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:26.690
There's a lot more ways
to get things done now.

00:09:26.690 --> 00:09:29.700
So that the typical
traditional limitations

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:32.020
that women have can be removed.

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:34.170
And technology makes it easy.

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:36.210
Because then in the
middle of a meeting,

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:39.090
I can still check on my son
in university in England.

00:09:39.090 --> 00:09:40.110
Just what's up?

00:09:40.110 --> 00:09:42.000
Send him a message or response.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:42.550
I'm going on.

00:09:42.550 --> 00:09:43.850
I've checked in for the day.

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.660
And I'm still
sitting at a meeting.

00:09:45.660 --> 00:09:48.109
So I think we can change.

00:09:48.109 --> 00:09:49.400
We can definitely move forward.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:50.356
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR: Great.

00:09:50.356 --> 00:09:51.481
OBY EZEKWESILI : Thank you.

00:09:51.481 --> 00:09:52.746
[APPLAUSE]

00:09:53.022 --> 00:09:55.480
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR: You're
raised some really important

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:55.980
points.

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:58.150
And I would like to
stay on those for a bit.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:00.050
You talked about some factors.

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:02.380
For example, choice
of spouse, right?

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:06.377
And a lot of women actually do
value having a balanced home

00:10:06.377 --> 00:10:07.210
and a peaceful home.

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:08.380
And that's very important.

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:12.180
And TY, very recently, you've
been very much in the press,

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:14.030
being instrumental
in transforming

00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:17.770
the life of a bread
seller, to become a model.

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:18.330
TY BELLO: OK.

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:20.870
I'm glad we're talking
about this glass, the glass

00:10:20.870 --> 00:10:25.680
ceiling and women making it
forward and pushing forward

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:27.040
in society.

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:30.780
My take on it is you
don't necessarily

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:34.345
have to be antagonistic
to break it.

00:10:34.345 --> 00:10:36.080
It can be done with wisdom.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.090
And it's all about maneuvering.

00:10:38.090 --> 00:10:42.260
I would rather carry
a man along, than

00:10:42.260 --> 00:10:44.401
drag him over kicking
and screaming, or going

00:10:44.401 --> 00:10:45.520
at it alone.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:48.550
I think psychologically,
it's better for most women

00:10:48.550 --> 00:10:52.550
when they have the corporation
of whoever they're with.

00:10:52.550 --> 00:10:55.250
Now, she said something
very important.

00:10:55.250 --> 00:10:57.510
And that is a point
where most people are not

00:10:57.510 --> 00:11:00.980
being mentored or taught enough,
is making that initial choice,

00:11:00.980 --> 00:11:04.500
to find out who you should
be with in the first place.

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:07.030
For instance, I knew I
wanted to be an artist.

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:09.991
And I had an
ex-boyfriend who said,

00:11:09.991 --> 00:11:11.490
I don't mind this
photography thing.

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:15.750
But I don't kind of see my
wife carrying cameras around.

00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:16.820
And I took it seriously.

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:19.730
I did not think it was
just something on the side.

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:22.710
I wasn't going to marry him and
hope that he would support me

00:11:22.710 --> 00:11:23.730
afterwards.

00:11:23.730 --> 00:11:27.060
So I knew, for instance,
that for this lady,

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:30.480
the only way we could go far
was if we had cooperation.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:34.730
Because you have to
realize that culture

00:11:34.730 --> 00:11:42.100
is a very, very big part
of the whole scenario here.

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:44.010
And you can't do away with it.

00:11:44.010 --> 00:11:46.140
You can't fight it, necessarily.

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:47.360
You can fight.

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:51.212
You can change, but with
wisdom, I think, yeah.

00:11:51.212 --> 00:11:52.920
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR:
Great, thank you.

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:56.550
Ibukun, what's
your take on that?

00:11:56.550 --> 00:11:58.380
IBUKUN AWOSIKA:
Well, to be honest,

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:03.260
I think half the battle
that women fight, here.

00:12:03.260 --> 00:12:07.690
It's because we tend
to live out of context.

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:10.050
You know, we're
all well-educated

00:12:10.050 --> 00:12:12.820
and quite exposed.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:14.530
We've been everywhere.

00:12:14.530 --> 00:12:16.710
And we've read [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:16.710 --> 00:12:19.180
We've watched a lot of movies.

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:21.880
And a lot of girls
then get up and really

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:26.130
just want to declare
that kind of liberty

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:28.300
that they think a
Western woman has.

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:33.110
The reality is, it's
an approach that is

00:12:33.110 --> 00:12:34.710
bound to fail from the onset.

00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:36.590
I always talk about strategy.

00:12:36.590 --> 00:12:39.420
There's no business
without a strategic plan.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:41.674
And we're all comfortable
to have a strategic plan

00:12:41.674 --> 00:12:43.590
for the next three years
of our business, five

00:12:43.590 --> 00:12:44.900
years of our business.

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:47.740
Why don't we have a
strategic plan for our life?

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:50.630
That's affects where
we really want to go.

00:12:50.630 --> 00:12:53.310
And when you're just got
a up a strategic plan

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:56.330
for your business, you
don't leave the context

00:12:56.330 --> 00:12:58.150
of your environment out of it.

00:12:58.150 --> 00:13:00.240
You take all the
factors around you

00:13:00.240 --> 00:13:03.960
into consideration, in making
the decisions of how you walk

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:05.980
around it to achieve success.

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:08.630
That's really how we,
as an African woman,

00:13:08.630 --> 00:13:11.520
and specifically as a
Nigerian, needs to look at it.

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:17.625
Reality is culture is on a
transformational journey.

00:13:17.625 --> 00:13:18.500
TY BELLO: Yes, it is.

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:21.010
IBUKUN AWOSIKA: Society
doesn't change overnight.

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:23.571
And even if it
does, I don't know,

00:13:23.571 --> 00:13:25.820
it would probably take a
million years for many things

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:27.490
in Nigeria to be totally done.

00:13:27.490 --> 00:13:29.440
As you can see, our
parents go to school

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.610
abroad, get to
the highest level.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:33.140
And just as they
retire, they decide

00:13:33.140 --> 00:13:34.890
they want to go and
live in their village.

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:36.440
And you really can't
understand how.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:39.340
The guy's left his village
since he was God knows what.

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:43.630
But it shows you that is quite
deep, this cultural thing.

00:13:43.630 --> 00:13:48.430
Now, what that should say to us
as women is this is my context.

00:13:48.430 --> 00:13:49.840
This is my environment.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:53.390
There's certain values that are
important in my environment.

00:13:53.390 --> 00:13:54.680
I want to play to win.

00:13:54.680 --> 00:13:55.740
That's my goal.

00:13:55.740 --> 00:13:59.280
How do I play to win
in my environment?

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:02.616
What does it cost me to
seek my husband's permission

00:14:02.616 --> 00:14:03.740
for something I want to do?

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:05.550
Not because I don't
know what I want to do.

00:14:05.550 --> 00:14:10.270
But is wisdom because I'd
rather run with his backing.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:12.740
And if I fail, I
have someone who's

00:14:12.740 --> 00:14:17.090
shoulder I can lean on, not
someone to say, I told you so.

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:17.840
You know?

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:19.120
I'll give you an example.

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:22.130
A young woman got transferred.

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:23.890
She works for a multinational.

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:30.800
And she always knew that she
will be up for her career

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:33.090
to go really far in
that multinational,

00:14:33.090 --> 00:14:36.600
she'll be up for international
posting at any point in time.

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:40.040
Now, if I'm in that kind of
setting, and then you marry,

00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:41.650
you're married.

00:14:41.650 --> 00:14:43.730
And you can see the
opportunity come in.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:45.530
And you'll be in
position for it.

00:14:45.530 --> 00:14:47.010
First and foremost,
because I know

00:14:47.010 --> 00:14:51.662
my job can have that context,
I will prepare my husband one

00:14:51.662 --> 00:14:52.370
way or the other.

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:54.930
It will be a conversation that
we would have had that one.

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:57.636
Even if you're pretending
sometimes, like he,

00:14:57.636 --> 00:15:00.780
you know they could just
transfer me to Mexico tomorrow.

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:02.510
How am I going to go to Mexico?

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:04.500
You, the children,
and all of that?

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:06.477
You're instigating
a conversation.

00:15:06.477 --> 00:15:07.810
But you're preparing the ground.

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:09.580
So you would hear his opinion.

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:11.400
And listening to
him will help you

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:14.500
to know how to
formulate the strategy

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:17.790
to work the environment
of the home, in case

00:15:17.790 --> 00:15:19.360
that situation arises.

00:15:19.360 --> 00:15:22.012
So that his mind is
already conditioned.

00:15:22.012 --> 00:15:23.970
And he may end up thinking
he is the one that's

00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:25.980
convinced you to take the
posting because he thinks

00:15:25.980 --> 00:15:26.896
he's good for the job.

00:15:26.896 --> 00:15:28.960
But you already know you
want to go to Mexico.

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:30.430
So it's not how.

00:15:30.430 --> 00:15:32.950
So I'm saying, he
gets the respect.

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:33.900
It gets the honor.

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:37.310
A man has a natural big ego.

00:15:37.310 --> 00:15:38.940
What are you going
to do about that?

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:41.530
The bottom line is, how
do you manage his ego,

00:15:41.530 --> 00:15:44.350
manage his respect,
and hist authority

00:15:44.350 --> 00:15:46.320
as the head of
the house in a way

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:47.932
that you still
achieve your goal?

00:15:47.932 --> 00:15:49.890
JULIET EHIMUAN-CHIAZOR:
So from the perspective

00:15:49.890 --> 00:15:54.480
of entrepreneurship, you have
been quite the entrepreneur.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:57.060
And I know you talk
about really focusing

00:15:57.060 --> 00:16:00.190
on ethics and integrity, in
building the Chair Centre

00:16:00.190 --> 00:16:00.870
Group.

00:16:00.870 --> 00:16:02.654
And you had some
challenging situations,

00:16:02.654 --> 00:16:04.070
which you were
able to turn around

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:06.150
for the good of the
business in the long run.

00:16:06.150 --> 00:16:09.440
What advice do you have
for entrepreneurs going

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:12.670
through challenges, from the
perspective of navigating

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:16.046
through standing for
what you believe in,

00:16:16.046 --> 00:16:18.170
holding your ground, and
actually being successful?

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:22.180
IBUKUN AWOSIKA: I think
the starting point

00:16:22.180 --> 00:16:25.270
is that you have to have a
conversation with yourself,

00:16:25.270 --> 00:16:28.440
at the very beginning,
and decide who you are

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:30.260
or who you want to be.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:32.630
You must decide what your
value system will be.

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:35.580
You can never wait
to get to a crossroad

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:38.360
before you determine what
your value system is.

00:16:38.360 --> 00:16:41.150
The reality is, if you
try to decide your value

00:16:41.150 --> 00:16:43.940
system at a crossroad,
the pressure of the moment

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:46.110
will force you in a
different direction.

00:16:46.110 --> 00:16:49.890
So what happened to me
was, as I was starting out

00:16:49.890 --> 00:16:53.700
as a young girl in my
20s, I became a Christian.

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:55.820
Because I did start
off as a Muslim.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:57.735
I was brought up
in a Muslim home.

00:16:57.735 --> 00:16:58.610
I became a Christian.

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:01.141
And then I read this book.

00:17:01.141 --> 00:17:05.619
It was written by some guy
about God owning his business.

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:07.619
And I found it very fascinating.

00:17:07.619 --> 00:17:10.500
And I made a decision that I
wanted God to own my business.

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.680
And God can't own a business
where the value system

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:14.700
isn't based on the Bible.

00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:20.089
So I built my own value
system on biblical principles.

00:17:20.089 --> 00:17:22.240
And with that
conviction, I decided

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:24.240
some things I will not do.

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:26.296
The first, before I
became a Christian,

00:17:26.296 --> 00:17:27.920
I started my business
for about a year.

00:17:27.920 --> 00:17:29.700
But even at the beginning
of the business,

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:31.560
without the biblical principles.

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:33.785
Based on just my
upbringing, I decided

00:17:33.785 --> 00:17:34.910
two things I will never do.

00:17:34.910 --> 00:17:37.459
I was never going to sleep
with a man to get a job.

00:17:37.459 --> 00:17:39.000
And I was never
going to pay a bribe.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.625
Now, everybody assured me there
were a perfect formula to fail,

00:17:41.625 --> 00:17:44.480
especially the bribe
in Nigerian context.

00:17:44.480 --> 00:17:48.200
But you know, I think we
underestimate Nigerians.

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:49.710
That's the one thing
I can tell you.

00:17:49.710 --> 00:17:53.160
Because if I built a business--
and this is our 28th year.

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:55.620
And I say that we've
lived by those principles,

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:57.350
then obviously there's
more than enough

00:17:57.350 --> 00:17:59.717
room in this environment to
build the kind of business

00:17:59.717 --> 00:18:00.300
that you want.

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:01.950
It's all about you.

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:05.660
And with those two
things said before me,

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:06.700
I started the journey.

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:08.924
Now, of course, there have
been many, many moments

00:18:08.924 --> 00:18:10.590
where those values
have been challenged.

00:18:10.590 --> 00:18:15.960
But I've been sometimes
really difficult and very

00:18:15.960 --> 00:18:18.550
sad moments have
taken the decision

00:18:18.550 --> 00:18:20.830
to stand by those
principles, paying

00:18:20.830 --> 00:18:23.090
a high price, many instances.

00:18:23.090 --> 00:18:25.000
But one thing I have
learned is this.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.300
If you want to build
something to last,

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:29.260
you need to build
on the right values.

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:32.030
If you build on compromise,
the same compromises

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:33.020
will destroy you.

00:18:33.020 --> 00:18:35.472
I mean, imagine a girl
who is willing to sleep

00:18:35.472 --> 00:18:36.680
with men to get the contract.

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:39.420
You're only attractive
before you're conquered.

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:41.380
But reality is once
the man slept with you

00:18:41.380 --> 00:18:45.180
once, your value is depreciated
by 100%, 80%, or 90%.

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:46.930
I mean, you can have
a repeat performance.

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:49.400
But he's overcome the challenge.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:50.440
So there's no big deal.

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:52.800
So he doesn't have to give
you the big contract anymore.

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:55.370
he can give that to the next
new conquest that he wants.

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:57.750
And you can get the peanut.

00:18:57.750 --> 00:19:00.280
If you pay a bribe,
yeah, there's

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:03.370
always somebody who is
willing to pay more than you.

00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:06.260
And after a while,
it's a tough game.

00:19:06.260 --> 00:19:09.210
I then decided
what I would rather

00:19:09.210 --> 00:19:15.420
invest in is to invest time to
build service and build quality

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:19.530
product, and make my company
indispensable to any customer

00:19:19.530 --> 00:19:21.810
that engages with us over time.

00:19:21.810 --> 00:19:24.919
And yes, you might be slower
than your peers at this stage,

00:19:24.919 --> 00:19:27.210
because there are some things
you're not willing to do.

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:30.010
But I've found in my
business that you're

00:19:30.010 --> 00:19:32.900
far more sustainable over time.

00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:35.580
And you know, at
crucial moments,

00:19:35.580 --> 00:19:38.300
those principals were tested.

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:41.320
Because like in 2004,
when the government said,

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:43.720
OK ban on everything
related to furniture,

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:46.170
it was a function of OK,
a bill that was-- I'd

00:19:46.170 --> 00:19:48.260
been in business
for 15 years then.

00:19:48.260 --> 00:19:49.870
Was I now going to
become a smuggler?

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:51.560
I wasn't going to.

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:54.400
Because my principal
value system

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:57.180
I determined in advance was
not going to support that.

00:19:57.180 --> 00:20:00.830
So the only option I had was
to do backward integration

00:20:00.830 --> 00:20:02.630
and invest in
factories to support.

00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:04.350
What we were doing
was producing.

00:20:04.350 --> 00:20:06.440
We started local
production originally.

00:20:06.440 --> 00:20:08.200
And then all the
factors in Nigeria

00:20:08.200 --> 00:20:10.750
didn't allow us to fulfill
the dream I wanted.

00:20:10.750 --> 00:20:13.670
So we started producing in OEM
factories around the world,

00:20:13.670 --> 00:20:15.920
and bringing the
components back and adding

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:17.190
to create our own line.

00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:21.096
So when the game changed,
all we did was OK, so what

00:20:21.096 --> 00:20:22.220
are we allowed to bring in?

00:20:22.220 --> 00:20:24.060
What are we not
allowed to bring in?

00:20:24.060 --> 00:20:27.140
And we started working
back, and started having

00:20:27.140 --> 00:20:29.080
JVs to produce in Nigeria.

00:20:29.080 --> 00:20:32.650
Ultimately, staying
by our principals

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:35.820
encouraged us to build the
necessary factories here.

00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:38.220
Now, I'll now tell
you the real offshoot.

00:20:38.220 --> 00:20:40.780
When people talk about
oh, I sit on this board,

00:20:40.780 --> 00:20:42.370
I sit on that board,
I do that now.

00:20:42.370 --> 00:20:45.400
Frankly speaking,
the things that

00:20:45.400 --> 00:20:49.940
actually made me
attractive to be invited

00:20:49.940 --> 00:20:52.410
to sit on a number of boards
were those same things

00:20:52.410 --> 00:20:54.730
that I went through
in those tough times.

00:20:54.730 --> 00:20:58.065
It was the lessons I learned by
staying true to my principles.

00:20:58.065 --> 00:20:59.860
It was the sacrifices I made.

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:03.400
Because I remember
when I was going

00:21:03.400 --> 00:21:05.270
to join the board of Cadbury.

00:21:05.270 --> 00:21:07.670
It was right after
Cadbury's crisis.

00:21:07.670 --> 00:21:11.100
And I got a call the day
before from a friend of mine

00:21:11.100 --> 00:21:13.517
that said, some people would
like to come and talk to you.

00:21:13.517 --> 00:21:15.266
And I said, well, I'm
travelling tomorrow.

00:21:15.266 --> 00:21:17.570
If they can see me tomorrow
morning, that will be fine.

00:21:17.570 --> 00:21:20.240
And two British gentleman
came to my house.

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:25.900
We had conversation for 2 and
1/2 hours, and all of that.

00:21:25.900 --> 00:21:30.660
Cadbury was basically trying
to set up a board of integrity.

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:33.700
And refusing to do
those things over time

00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:35.730
was how I got on their list.

00:21:35.730 --> 00:21:37.360
You never know who is watching.

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:38.120
You don't know who is watching.

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:39.860
Everybody is watching
what you're doing.

00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:43.029
People might hail you, even when
you're doing the wrong thing.

00:21:43.029 --> 00:21:44.570
You sound successful
and all of that.

00:21:44.570 --> 00:21:46.927
But when the chips are
down, you know somebody

00:21:46.927 --> 00:21:48.010
is going to say something.

00:21:48.010 --> 00:21:49.010
Because somebody is watching.

00:21:49.010 --> 00:21:50.420
And that's exactly
what happened.

00:21:50.420 --> 00:21:52.180
They had a
[INAUDIBLE] list of 30

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:54.950
that was whittled down to 8,
that was whittled down to 6.

00:21:54.950 --> 00:21:56.980
And then they ended
up with a list

00:21:56.980 --> 00:21:59.210
of three-- myself, Atedo
Peterside, and [INAUDIBLE],

00:21:59.210 --> 00:22:00.084
who joined the board.

00:22:00.084 --> 00:22:03.600
And I've been on the board
of Cadbury since 2009.

00:22:03.600 --> 00:22:06.530
The day I was invited to
have a chat with the group

00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:10.960
chair of FBN Holding, he was
the Chair of the [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:13.200
Bank, PLC then.

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:16.390
It was simply for me to be
recruited to be Chairman

00:22:16.390 --> 00:22:17.620
of the insurance company.

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:20.490
Because they were having
a startup company.

00:22:20.490 --> 00:22:24.176
That is a joint venture with
Sanlam, of South Africa.

00:22:24.176 --> 00:22:25.550
And they were
looking for someone

00:22:25.550 --> 00:22:28.330
who had good experience
in driving a startup

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:29.820
with international partnership.

00:22:29.820 --> 00:22:32.080
Now, it was the
challenge of 2004

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:34.650
that led me to a joint
venture partnership

00:22:34.650 --> 00:22:37.040
with the largest French
manufacturer of [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:38.550
So I had that experience.

00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:41.800
I had stock to my values
through the trial period.

00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:44.370
And though every knowledge
I gained within that period

00:22:44.370 --> 00:22:46.540
was what they needed for
what they wanted to do.

00:22:46.540 --> 00:22:48.070
And that's how I was invited.

00:22:48.070 --> 00:22:50.419
I actually had the conversation
about being the chair

00:22:50.419 --> 00:22:51.460
of the insurance company.

00:22:51.460 --> 00:22:54.730
But I didn't know that to even
be the chair of the insurance

00:22:54.730 --> 00:22:57.170
company, I had to get on
the board of the bank.

00:22:57.170 --> 00:23:00.139
So a month after, I just
got a message that said,

00:23:00.139 --> 00:23:02.180
you've been appointed to
the board of First Bank.

00:23:02.180 --> 00:23:03.850
I'm, like, board of First Bank?

00:23:03.850 --> 00:23:04.650
How?

00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:07.510
I was asked about joining
the insurance company.

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:11.000
So things you do for
the right reasons,

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:13.330
ultimately, people are watching.

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:15.070
Somebody will notice.

00:23:15.070 --> 00:23:16.680
And it would create value.

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:20.070
So doing the right thing has
its own reward over time.

00:23:20.070 --> 00:23:22.620
You might bear
pain for a season.

00:23:22.620 --> 00:23:24.920
But there's a time when
everything comes together.

00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:28.740
