00:36:20.610 --> 00:36:24.590
can be a very important, as
part of the way of shattering

00:36:24.590 --> 00:36:27.420
the glass ceiling.

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:32.550
But where, I would say,
that I have come face

00:36:32.550 --> 00:36:36.640
to face with this matter
of oh boy, you're a woman,

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:40.310
is actually not the
workplace experience.

00:36:40.310 --> 00:36:43.580
It's the global
experience, where

00:36:43.580 --> 00:36:47.830
culturally-- which is
part of the glass ceiling

00:36:47.830 --> 00:36:52.580
that we see in the country
a lot-- people sort of

00:36:52.580 --> 00:36:59.610
have make presumptions about
how power relationship ought

00:36:59.610 --> 00:37:01.020
to look like.

00:37:01.020 --> 00:37:03.360
If they've made
assumptions, and if they

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:06.370
have these presumptuous
attitude, then what

00:37:06.370 --> 00:37:09.980
they're going to think it
is why should a woman appear

00:37:09.980 --> 00:37:11.420
to be strong?

00:37:11.420 --> 00:37:15.160
So you can have instances where
people say, you are so strong.

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:16.540
Oh!

00:37:16.540 --> 00:37:21.160
I wonder who Oby
Esekwesili's husband is.

00:37:21.160 --> 00:37:24.330
And I'm thinking
to myself, if only

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:27.900
I knew that I have
a husband who,

00:37:27.900 --> 00:37:29.830
if he just gives me
one eye like this,

00:37:29.830 --> 00:37:33.680
I would just find
in seat quietly.

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:35.620
Because, you know?

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:36.120
You know.

00:37:36.120 --> 00:37:37.328
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: Yeah.

00:37:37.328 --> 00:37:40.250
OBY ESEKWESILI: So that's my
own experience of glass ceiling.

00:37:40.250 --> 00:37:42.650
It's a macro, level 1.

00:37:42.650 --> 00:37:47.720
It's not the level where, in
my profession, in my work,

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:50.870
anyone has said to
me, you're a woman.

00:37:50.870 --> 00:37:54.092
So there are limitations
that we must place on you.

00:37:54.092 --> 00:37:55.300
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: Yeah.

00:37:55.300 --> 00:37:59.430
I certainly do agree that
context varies from one person

00:37:59.430 --> 00:38:02.170
to another, and actually
plays a key role

00:38:02.170 --> 00:38:04.010
in looking at this holistically.

00:38:04.010 --> 00:38:09.150
And the fact that the mental
block is a very big one

00:38:09.150 --> 00:38:10.480
to break through.

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:13.050
And thinking about
that mental block,

00:38:13.050 --> 00:38:17.240
sometimes that comes
from the cultural context

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:18.420
that we find ourselves in.

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:20.770
So my next question
would be to TY.

00:38:20.770 --> 00:38:22.300
And thank you for staying on.

00:38:22.300 --> 00:38:23.169
TY BELLO: Thank you.

00:38:23.169 --> 00:38:24.460
OBY ESEKWESILI: You're welcome.

00:38:24.460 --> 00:38:26.860
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
From a cultural perspective,

00:38:26.860 --> 00:38:31.200
what role do you see
our culture playing

00:38:31.200 --> 00:38:36.440
around either creating limiting
or expansive opportunities

00:38:36.440 --> 00:38:38.090
for women?

00:38:38.090 --> 00:38:44.720
TY BELLO: Well, like she said,
I can only speak for myself

00:38:44.720 --> 00:38:45.843
in certain instances.

00:38:45.843 --> 00:38:47.884
Because I know, for
instance, I'm a photographer.

00:38:47.884 --> 00:38:51.140
And I remember when I
started making images,

00:38:51.140 --> 00:38:53.420
and my images started
getting noticed.

00:38:53.420 --> 00:38:55.410
TY Bello was a man.

00:38:55.410 --> 00:38:57.900
And wherever I showed
up, people were shocked.

00:38:57.900 --> 00:39:00.280
And they're, like, oh,
is your guy on his way?

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:02.116
And I'm like, this is he.

00:39:02.116 --> 00:39:03.034
You know?

00:39:03.034 --> 00:39:04.450
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
She is he.

00:39:04.450 --> 00:39:05.520
TY BELLO: She is he.

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:06.510
You know?

00:39:06.510 --> 00:39:10.690
But I believe it's
not just culture.

00:39:10.690 --> 00:39:12.800
I also think it's history.

00:39:12.800 --> 00:39:15.100
How many women have done this?

00:39:15.100 --> 00:39:17.160
And how many women
have done that?

00:39:17.160 --> 00:39:19.410
So if no woman has
done this, so what

00:39:19.410 --> 00:39:22.540
gives you the audacity
to think that you can?

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:24.690
I can give an example.

00:39:24.690 --> 00:39:29.140
When I got the opportunity,
in the last administration,

00:39:29.140 --> 00:39:36.950
to document the presidency on
a very, very intimate level,

00:39:36.950 --> 00:39:39.370
and to go behind the scenes
and actually photograph what

00:39:39.370 --> 00:39:43.850
happened, I realized that it
was important for history.

00:39:43.850 --> 00:39:45.670
I don't know who Abacha was.

00:39:45.670 --> 00:39:48.070
I don't know how he smiled.

00:39:48.070 --> 00:39:51.340
I don't know who
got to document him.

00:39:51.340 --> 00:39:54.890
Yes, we saw him behind
the dark sunglasses.

00:39:54.890 --> 00:39:56.980
We saw him shake a few hands.

00:39:56.980 --> 00:39:59.570
But we never saw any
vulnerable moment.

00:39:59.570 --> 00:40:01.690
We never saw him in doubt.

00:40:01.690 --> 00:40:05.740
And I felt like, OK, I need
to take on this job well.

00:40:05.740 --> 00:40:08.370
And I know that I'm
surrounded by men.

00:40:08.370 --> 00:40:10.360
And I know that I'm
surrounded by security,

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:13.280
that are going to try and
create boundaries for me,

00:40:13.280 --> 00:40:17.250
to tell me how far I can
go based on how far people

00:40:17.250 --> 00:40:18.630
in history have gone.

00:40:18.630 --> 00:40:23.220
So for instance, when
people in government walk,

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:26.790
you don't move close
beyond a certain distance.

00:40:26.790 --> 00:40:29.350
You don't move close
beyond a certain level.

00:40:29.350 --> 00:40:30.250
And I'm like, no.

00:40:30.250 --> 00:40:31.390
I want to get this shot.

00:40:31.390 --> 00:40:32.690
I'm shooting wide angle.

00:40:32.690 --> 00:40:34.000
I need to move closer.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.080
So it was always a struggle.

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:39.780
But I do realize something--
that because I fought hard,

00:40:39.780 --> 00:40:42.870
and because I constantly
broke barriers,

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:46.590
people who have come after me
have found it a little easier.

00:40:46.590 --> 00:40:48.460
They haven't had to explain.

00:40:48.460 --> 00:40:50.510
And they haven't
had to show work.

00:40:50.510 --> 00:40:52.560
They haven't had to
stand for 72 hours

00:40:52.560 --> 00:40:54.110
to let them know,
yes, I'm a woman.

00:40:54.110 --> 00:40:54.930
But I am tough.

00:40:54.930 --> 00:40:55.580
And I'm strong.

00:40:55.580 --> 00:40:57.660
I will hold my
camera, two of them.

00:40:57.660 --> 00:41:00.220
I'll hold my cameras in
my hand for 72 hours.

00:41:00.220 --> 00:41:01.590
And I will not budge.

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:03.700
Because I'm serious
about what I'm doing.

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:06.620
So sometimes I think
it's working extra hard,

00:41:06.620 --> 00:41:10.530
knowing that it's
not just about you

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:12.350
and your own
personal experience.

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:15.510
But realizing that every
time you push boundaries,

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:17.420
you're creating and
you're writing history.

00:41:17.420 --> 00:41:21.310
You're telling a new story,
that somebody else can say, hey,

00:41:21.310 --> 00:41:23.040
this is how it's done.

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:23.835
You create new.

00:41:23.835 --> 00:41:26.010
This is how it's done.

00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:26.550
You know?

00:41:26.550 --> 00:41:28.190
[APPLAUSE]

00:41:29.560 --> 00:41:30.930
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: Great.

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:34.290
And you've been quite
successful in transitioning

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:36.822
from a singer/songwriter
to a photographer.

00:41:36.822 --> 00:41:38.780
TY BELLO: Oh, now I'm
trying to transition back

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:41.120
It's kind of tough now.

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:43.710
OBY ESEKWESILI: So I think
you've alluded to that.

00:41:43.710 --> 00:41:46.720
But just in a bit more
detail, some of the things

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:48.650
that you did, or
your unique selling

00:41:48.650 --> 00:41:51.160
point, around being able
to successfully make

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:52.680
that transition.

00:41:52.680 --> 00:41:56.340
And actually, being
dominant in an industry that

00:41:56.340 --> 00:41:59.110
is highly occupied by men.

00:42:01.644 --> 00:42:03.560
TY BELLO: It's about
creating new definitions.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:06.590
I remember when I told
my mom and her friends

00:42:06.590 --> 00:42:12.684
that I wanted to be a
photographer in 1999, a very

00:42:12.684 --> 00:42:14.350
close auntie, who
really cared about me,

00:42:14.350 --> 00:42:16.611
was, like, [INAUDIBLE] why now?

00:42:16.611 --> 00:42:17.360
Do you understand?

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:19.040
Because prior to
that, in her mind,

00:42:19.040 --> 00:42:21.960
a photographer is someone who is
struggling and carries a camera

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:23.520
and is with bathroom sleepers.

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:24.255
You know?

00:42:24.255 --> 00:42:28.622
They did not have a picture
of what I was aspiring to.

00:42:28.622 --> 00:42:30.080
Unfortunately,
thank goodness, they

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:32.210
didn't know that I didn't
have a picture either.

00:42:32.210 --> 00:42:35.930
It's just that I had a very
strong conviction that this

00:42:35.930 --> 00:42:37.230
is something I'm meant to do.

00:42:37.230 --> 00:42:38.813
I don't know why I'm
meant to do this.

00:42:38.813 --> 00:42:40.860
But I know that I can do this.

00:42:40.860 --> 00:42:43.680
But I also found out
that it's all the same.

00:42:43.680 --> 00:42:45.890
It's about composition
and telling stories.

00:42:45.890 --> 00:42:47.570
You write a song,
you tell a story.

00:42:47.570 --> 00:42:49.300
You make an image,
you tell a story.

00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:52.560
What I do with my work is
to tell people stories.

00:42:52.560 --> 00:42:54.800
Even when I take a
portrait of a woman,

00:42:54.800 --> 00:42:57.470
I want her to see
herself differently.

00:42:57.470 --> 00:42:58.500
Do you understand?

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:02.534
It's so extreme that sometimes
I would photograph someone.

00:43:02.534 --> 00:43:04.450
And I would meet them
two years down the line,

00:43:04.450 --> 00:43:05.408
I can't recognize them.

00:43:05.408 --> 00:43:08.810
Because I have, in my
head, created this persona.

00:43:08.810 --> 00:43:10.090
And that is all that I see.

00:43:10.090 --> 00:43:15.210
I see every woman at her
highest and most beautiful,

00:43:15.210 --> 00:43:16.590
and the strongest.

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:19.400
And I sell them that story.

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:22.010
And when they believe
the story, they

00:43:22.010 --> 00:43:24.430
become that person
in front of my lens.

00:43:24.430 --> 00:43:26.380
And it's is the same
thing with music.

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:29.200
So I find it very easy to go
back and forth between the two

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:29.700
mediums.

00:43:29.700 --> 00:43:30.720
Because it's exactly
the same thing.

00:43:30.720 --> 00:43:32.470
You're trying to inspire people.

00:43:32.470 --> 00:43:35.552
You're trying to show them
this is really who you are.

00:43:35.552 --> 00:43:39.440
Or even if I'm just
reiterating who I am,

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:41.530
you know, and becoming a
mirror for other people.

00:43:41.530 --> 00:43:45.560
And so that's why it's so
easy to go between the two art

00:43:45.560 --> 00:43:46.514
forms for me.

00:43:46.514 --> 00:43:47.930
JULIET EHUMIAN
CHIAZOR: Fantastic.

00:43:47.930 --> 00:43:48.290
TY BELLO: Thank you.

00:43:48.290 --> 00:43:49.831
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
That's great.

00:43:49.831 --> 00:43:53.050
And I think that's
very powerful as well,

00:43:53.050 --> 00:43:56.830
getting people to see the
grandest version of themselves,

00:43:56.830 --> 00:43:59.990
and believing that, and
having that come through

00:43:59.990 --> 00:44:00.870
in photography.

00:44:00.870 --> 00:44:01.672
TY BELLO: Yeah.

00:44:01.672 --> 00:44:03.130
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
Oby, you've

00:44:03.130 --> 00:44:06.930
been very vocal about the Bring
Back Our Girls Campaign, which

00:44:06.930 --> 00:44:09.920
