00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:47.390
out after many weeks of
social media advocacy,

00:44:47.390 --> 00:44:52.375
and we went to do a physical
advocacy by turning up

00:44:52.375 --> 00:44:55.090
at the unity fountain, a lot
of the people who came out

00:44:55.090 --> 00:44:56.900
were men also.

00:44:56.900 --> 00:45:01.150
But it was mostly
women that co-convened.

00:45:01.150 --> 00:45:05.030
So we had [INAUDIBLE]
of a Laos man

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:08.990
who was really the
young woman that said,

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:10.220
social media is good.

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:14.070
But it looks like
these people are not.

00:45:14.070 --> 00:45:16.130
So it's important that
you see that people

00:45:16.130 --> 00:45:18.484
are on the straight,
really impress that.

00:45:18.484 --> 00:45:19.900
JULIET EHUMIAN
CHIAZOR: Of course.

00:45:19.900 --> 00:45:23.300
OBY EZEKWESILI: --in
the rescue of the girls.

00:45:23.300 --> 00:45:26.560
And then Miriam
[INAUDIBLE], saw that

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:30.530
through [INAUDIBLE] and
I, and then [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:30.530 --> 00:45:35.740
So we then began to convene
with people to come out

00:45:35.740 --> 00:45:37.422
of that [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:37.422 --> 00:45:40.175
And many men came out.

00:45:40.175 --> 00:45:48.310
And for majority of the men that
have connected to the tragedy,

00:45:48.310 --> 00:45:52.170
it's been because
they would always

00:45:52.170 --> 00:45:57.770
say, I don't want to
imagine my daughter

00:45:57.770 --> 00:46:02.720
in the hand of terrorists, or
in the hands of terrorists.

00:46:02.720 --> 00:46:12.520
If we set the standard that it
is perfectly OK for the poorer

00:46:12.520 --> 00:46:17.880
segment of our society to good
through tragedies of the kind

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:20.240
that the Chibok community
has gone through,

00:46:20.240 --> 00:46:22.530
that the kind of the
parents of our Chibok girls

00:46:22.530 --> 00:46:25.320
have gone through,
and we, the elite,

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:28.750
can find the moment to
sit down and discuss

00:46:28.750 --> 00:46:34.190
whether it was-- should they
have done this or should they?

00:46:34.190 --> 00:46:36.570
Oh, come on.

00:46:36.570 --> 00:46:41.070
If children that
I give birth to,

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:48.050
or any of the other elite class
give birth to were abducted,

00:46:48.050 --> 00:46:52.290
you think the government would
have kept quiet for as long

00:46:52.290 --> 00:46:53.330
as it did?

00:46:53.330 --> 00:46:55.550
It would never have happened.

00:46:55.550 --> 00:47:00.800
It's simply that we are now
a society where we actually

00:47:00.800 --> 00:47:06.350
are insulated and isolated
from the poorer segment.

00:47:06.350 --> 00:47:10.440
So if it happens, it's one
of the things that happened.

00:47:10.440 --> 00:47:16.180
We can comfortably just
walk on by, walk on by.

00:47:16.180 --> 00:47:18.490
I command, for our Chibok
girls, on the basis

00:47:18.490 --> 00:47:24.370
of my sense of outrage that
those girls were completely

00:47:24.370 --> 00:47:28.230
being ignored by the
system that should

00:47:28.230 --> 00:47:31.560
have responded to
the distress call

00:47:31.560 --> 00:47:34.110
that they had been abducted.

00:47:34.110 --> 00:47:36.868
The issue is where
are the Chibok girls?

00:47:36.868 --> 00:47:39.770
Where are girls
who went to school?

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:43.070
If you asked me to explain
my personal connection

00:47:43.070 --> 00:47:45.890
to their story, that's
easy and simple.

00:47:45.890 --> 00:47:47.850
And I would do it.

00:47:47.850 --> 00:47:54.490
Brono State was the key state
alongside [? Ubi, ?] that

00:47:54.490 --> 00:47:56.930
when I was Minister
of Education, had

00:47:56.930 --> 00:48:03.360
the worst poverty level in
education, girls and boys.

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:06.770
So for every four
young men in school,

00:48:06.770 --> 00:48:09.540
only one girl in school.

00:48:09.540 --> 00:48:14.310
And we needed to bridge
this disparity in education.

00:48:14.310 --> 00:48:17.800
So Brono state was a
profile sate for us.

00:48:17.800 --> 00:48:20.650
In fact, it was a major
state of intervention.

00:48:20.650 --> 00:48:26.790
It was this lovely young
woman, Ayesha [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:26.790 --> 00:48:32.540
was my task team person
for gender education,

00:48:32.540 --> 00:48:35.290
you know, girl child
education reforms.

00:48:35.290 --> 00:48:38.090
So for a new state,
it was major.

00:48:38.090 --> 00:48:45.130
Now, when those girls were
abducted, I was angry.

00:48:45.130 --> 00:48:48.510
Because I sort of
thought, so parents

00:48:48.510 --> 00:48:52.720
who were convinced, in a
very difficult environment,

00:48:52.720 --> 00:48:58.490
to send their doctors to school,
then we didn't safeguard them,

00:48:58.490 --> 00:49:00.450
they are gone.

00:49:00.450 --> 00:49:02.320
And they are with Boko Haram.

00:49:02.320 --> 00:49:04.340
And all we're going
to do, as a society,

00:49:04.340 --> 00:49:06.900
is say, another
one bites the dust.

00:49:07.797 --> 00:49:09.380
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
Totally agree.

00:49:09.380 --> 00:49:10.270
OBY EZEKWESILI: I
wasn't going to.

00:49:10.270 --> 00:49:11.436
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: Yes.

00:49:11.436 --> 00:49:16.700
I think, definitely,
it goes without saying,

00:49:16.700 --> 00:49:19.450
that fact that it is a
tragedy in our society,

00:49:19.450 --> 00:49:23.630
to have that happen, because
you have been such a powerhouse,

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:25.520
standing firm for
what you believe in.

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:28.130
So it's really
speaking to people

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:31.344
who go through
situations where you're

00:49:31.344 --> 00:49:32.510
trying to fight for a cause.

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:37.360
You're trying to take a stand,
either as a man or a woman.

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:39.360
But in this context, as a woman.

00:49:39.360 --> 00:49:44.240
And then you're having a
lot of external challenges

00:49:44.240 --> 00:49:46.640
and feedback, being able
to really stand firm

00:49:46.640 --> 00:49:49.870
in that, inspiring
people in that situation.

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:53.740
OBY EZEKWESILI: No, I get
your point, which is basically

00:49:53.740 --> 00:49:58.020
to say to people in
my response, you've

00:49:58.020 --> 00:50:00.280
got to set your
eyes on the ball.

00:50:00.280 --> 00:50:03.600
You know, the girls were more
important than anything anybody

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:04.100
was doing.

00:50:04.100 --> 00:50:06.630
I mean, one of the
things that happened

00:50:06.630 --> 00:50:08.920
in the course of
the advocacy, where

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:12.850
young men were sent to beat
us up, at the Unity Fountain.

00:50:12.850 --> 00:50:14.490
And some of those
young men, they

00:50:14.490 --> 00:50:18.060
would run all the way
to try to hit at me.

00:50:18.060 --> 00:50:21.830
And something would say to
them, we can't hit this woman.

00:50:21.830 --> 00:50:23.930
And they would run back.

00:50:23.930 --> 00:50:27.460
They hit a couple of our people.

00:50:27.460 --> 00:50:30.100
But they would come
all the way again.

00:50:30.100 --> 00:50:33.350
And they would sort of,
like, wanting to push.

00:50:33.350 --> 00:50:35.580
And something would
just hold them back.

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:37.290
And they would run back.

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:39.300
I saw that.

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:41.720
So whatever it is that
you can experience,

00:50:41.720 --> 00:50:44.430
we experienced in this advocacy.

00:50:44.430 --> 00:50:49.840
And for me, it was one
of the saddest things.

00:50:49.840 --> 00:50:53.310
But what you've got
to say to yourself,

00:50:53.310 --> 00:50:56.645
taking that inspirational
window on this,

00:50:56.645 --> 00:51:02.320
is look-- what costs
can I possibly pay now,

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:07.210
that can come close
to what these girls?

00:51:07.210 --> 00:51:14.200
I keep wondering, that 219 young
women interested in education.

00:51:14.200 --> 00:51:16.850
Can you imagine,
with all that they've

00:51:16.850 --> 00:51:22.970
been through, that we then find
these girls and rescue them?

00:51:22.970 --> 00:51:25.800
These girls would be
the greatest symbol

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:26.750
for girl child--

00:51:26.750 --> 00:51:28.010
AUDIENCE: Education.

00:51:28.010 --> 00:51:28.660
OBY EZEKWESILI: You understand?

00:51:28.660 --> 00:51:30.140
They will be the
greatest symbol.

00:51:30.140 --> 00:51:30.540
JULIET EHUMIAN
CHIAZOR: Absolutely.

00:51:30.540 --> 00:51:32.400
OBY EZEKWESILI: All
through the ages,

00:51:32.400 --> 00:51:36.190
any other parent that would
say, my child would not

00:51:36.190 --> 00:51:37.610
go to school.

00:51:37.610 --> 00:51:42.980
These children would be like
a reflector saying to them,

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:44.470
are you really sure?

00:51:44.470 --> 00:51:45.670
Just look at me.

00:51:45.670 --> 00:51:47.240
I went through all of this.

00:51:47.240 --> 00:51:50.380
I have now gone back and
completed my education.

00:51:50.380 --> 00:51:52.314
See how I am.

00:51:52.314 --> 00:51:54.480
Are you saying that like
daughter cannot be like me?

00:51:54.480 --> 00:51:57.710
It would be you and I,
now needing to plead.

00:51:57.710 --> 00:52:01.410
It would be those girls
making a clear statement.

00:52:01.410 --> 00:52:04.702
And it would be legacy
for the people of Chibok.

00:52:04.702 --> 00:52:06.410
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:52:06.410 --> 00:52:10.830
Especially as we talk about
education, education for women

00:52:10.830 --> 00:52:13.990
at all levels, in the
rural areas and everywhere.

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:17.550
As a nation, we have a
responsibility to the girls.

00:52:17.550 --> 00:52:26.220
And I think we are all united in
our intentions and our prayers,

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:29.920
that the girls do actually
come back home safely

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:31.030
to their families.

00:52:31.030 --> 00:52:36.530
What's then, the biggest impact
or cost of speaking your mind?

00:52:36.530 --> 00:52:39.210
Not necessarily about
this campaign in General

00:52:39.210 --> 00:52:41.840
OBY EZEKWESILI: Yes.

00:52:41.840 --> 00:52:45.780
And knock on my head, when
I was younger, you know?

00:52:45.780 --> 00:52:47.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:48.700 --> 00:52:49.907
You can relate, right?

00:52:49.907 --> 00:52:51.220
They did it to you also.

00:52:51.220 --> 00:52:52.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:52.130 --> 00:52:53.390
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: I
think we can all relate.

00:52:53.390 --> 00:52:54.223
OBY EZEKWESILI: Yes!

00:52:54.223 --> 00:52:55.815
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:57.510 --> 00:53:02.000
But it was helpful
that I had parents

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:05.210
that encouraged a voice.

00:53:05.210 --> 00:53:06.050
You know?

00:53:06.050 --> 00:53:07.810
They encouraged voice.

00:53:07.810 --> 00:53:11.810
They wanted us to take
ownership of our conviction.

00:53:11.810 --> 00:53:16.730
So my dad always used the time,
courage of conviction a lot,

00:53:16.730 --> 00:53:18.330
in raising us.

00:53:18.330 --> 00:53:24.900
And so a lot of the
times when I think

00:53:24.900 --> 00:53:31.940
of my opinion, my
view on an issue,

00:53:31.940 --> 00:53:37.670
I am saying it an
expression of my values?

00:53:37.670 --> 00:53:39.570
If it's an expression
of my values,

00:53:39.570 --> 00:53:42.630
I'm not prepared to negotiate.

00:53:42.630 --> 00:53:47.020
Because it's OK to
negotiate everything.

00:53:47.020 --> 00:53:48.510
But my values?

00:53:48.510 --> 00:53:50.010
No.

00:53:50.010 --> 00:53:52.470
I wouldn't negotiate my values.

00:53:52.470 --> 00:53:58.500
My voice on issues
are a reflection

00:53:58.500 --> 00:54:00.830
of the values that
I hold strong,

00:54:00.830 --> 00:54:02.796
and that I hold dear to.

00:54:02.796 --> 00:54:03.296
Yeah.

00:54:03.296 --> 00:54:04.716
TY BELLO: That's fantastic.

00:54:04.716 --> 00:54:06.132
JULIET EHUMIAN
CHIAZOR: Fantastic.

00:54:06.132 --> 00:54:07.000
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:07.060 --> 00:54:08.560
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
When we look

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:10.510
at the context in
the country today,

00:54:10.510 --> 00:54:12.050
we've got a lot of challenges.

00:54:12.050 --> 00:54:15.340
We have a devaluation
of the naira,

00:54:15.340 --> 00:54:17.940
various corrupt practices, etc.

00:54:17.940 --> 00:54:20.700
What advice do you have
for young people in Nigeria

00:54:20.700 --> 00:54:24.560
today, in terms of how
they can apply themselves,

00:54:24.560 --> 00:54:27.960
not giving up on any
dreams that they have,

00:54:27.960 --> 00:54:31.420
you can still be the
best that you can be.

00:54:31.420 --> 00:54:34.270
You can still come out of
all of this in triumph.

00:54:37.040 --> 00:54:41.460
OBY EZEKWESILI: My
first thing would

00:54:41.460 --> 00:54:48.940
be that the flip side of
every crisis situation

00:54:48.940 --> 00:54:55.720
is an opportunity
waiting to be harnessed.

00:54:55.720 --> 00:55:01.530
And so if there is anything
that a young person should

00:55:01.530 --> 00:55:03.810
be thinking about
right now, that

00:55:03.810 --> 00:55:08.110
would be what are the problems
that this particular moment

00:55:08.110 --> 00:55:11.730
requires people to be solving?

00:55:11.730 --> 00:55:16.230
What are the problems that
go with a time like this?

00:55:16.230 --> 00:55:19.020
Because if I can
identify those problems,

00:55:19.020 --> 00:55:22.720
and I can figure out the
solutions to those problems,

00:55:22.720 --> 00:55:26.220
I actually stand a chance of
not just solving problems,

00:55:26.220 --> 00:55:29.530
but having to a living.

00:55:29.530 --> 00:55:33.410
So if it is basically about
people trying to figure out

00:55:33.410 --> 00:55:35.510
what they can do
for a living, that

00:55:35.510 --> 00:55:37.460
would be a good
way to think of it.

00:55:37.460 --> 00:55:41.400
Because in crisis situation,
existing solutions

00:55:41.400 --> 00:55:42.230
no longer work.

00:55:42.230 --> 00:55:42.920
Right?

00:55:42.920 --> 00:55:48.210
Because existing solutions were
OK for a different context.

00:55:48.210 --> 00:55:49.200
You know?

00:55:49.200 --> 00:55:52.770
So thinking of it that
way just sort of makes

00:55:52.770 --> 00:55:55.980
you an entrepreneur.

00:55:55.980 --> 00:55:58.560
And then the
entrepreneurial mindset

00:55:58.560 --> 00:56:01.480
is the mindset of
the problem solver.

00:56:01.480 --> 00:56:04.750
And so you've got to
think of it that way.

00:56:04.750 --> 00:56:08.330
Because then it
unburdens you from saying

00:56:08.330 --> 00:56:10.566
we're all in trouble.

00:56:10.566 --> 00:56:12.690
You can distinguish yourself.

00:56:12.690 --> 00:56:16.810
I can identify the various
problems or the different sets

00:56:16.810 --> 00:56:18.285
of segments of society.

00:56:18.285 --> 00:56:19.410
And this what I can solve--

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:20.070
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: And the
opportunities that it creates.

00:56:20.070 --> 00:56:22.111
OBY EZEKWESILI: --and
these are the opportunities

00:56:22.111 --> 00:56:22.940
that are created.

00:56:22.940 --> 00:56:28.660
Then the second thing has to be
if I am in a changing context,

00:56:28.660 --> 00:56:33.880
then I need to be thinking,
am I equipped for this change?

00:56:33.880 --> 00:56:35.770
Am I equipped to handle it?

00:56:35.770 --> 00:56:38.930
You know, because as
circumstances change,

00:56:38.930 --> 00:56:44.890
the skills with which you're
going to have to deal with,

00:56:44.890 --> 00:56:48.750
the changing context
would have to change also.

00:56:48.750 --> 00:56:52.810
But if you still stuck
in person that you've

00:56:52.810 --> 00:56:56.982
been, in the expectations
that you've had,

00:56:56.982 --> 00:57:01.620
in the possibilities that you
can see, they you're stuck.

00:57:01.620 --> 00:57:04.330
You know, it's a dangerous
place to be stuck,

00:57:04.330 --> 00:57:07.050
just knowing what
you knew yesterday.

00:57:07.050 --> 00:57:09.140
Yesterday is gone, people.

00:57:09.140 --> 00:57:11.380
Today is new.

00:57:11.380 --> 00:57:13.120
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
Needs new ideas.

00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:15.604
OBY EZEKWESILI: And every
new day requires new skills--

00:57:15.604 --> 00:57:17.020
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
New ideas.

00:57:17.020 --> 00:57:21.250
OBY EZEKWESILI: New thoughts,
new ideas, new ways,

00:57:21.250 --> 00:57:25.720
new partnerships, new
orientations, new attitudes.

00:57:25.720 --> 00:57:33.910
And then a number three would
be to actually reach out.

00:57:33.910 --> 00:57:35.680
Reach out.

00:57:35.680 --> 00:57:39.310
It's a threat to be too
small in a world that

00:57:39.310 --> 00:57:41.110
is more and more global.

00:57:41.110 --> 00:57:41.610
OK?

00:57:41.610 --> 00:57:44.390
So you must reach out.

00:57:44.390 --> 00:57:48.120
I see some of the brilliance
of the generation,

00:57:48.120 --> 00:57:49.940
your generation.

00:57:49.940 --> 00:57:52.050
I see the brilliance.

00:57:52.050 --> 00:57:58.570
But I also see a certain
amount of self adulation,

00:57:58.570 --> 00:58:04.340
and a sense of
dysfunctional individualism.

00:58:04.340 --> 00:58:08.535
So people just love
the idea that it's

00:58:08.535 --> 00:58:13.600
I am the champion who is doing
this thing, all by myself.

00:58:13.600 --> 00:58:16.352
No, today's world is a world
of collaborative partnerships.

00:58:16.352 --> 00:58:18.560
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR: TY,
what's your take on that?

00:58:18.560 --> 00:58:20.360
TY BELLO: I'd like
to add to that.

00:58:20.360 --> 00:58:23.570
This is the age of social media.

00:58:23.570 --> 00:58:26.160
And social media
means communication

00:58:26.160 --> 00:58:27.923
and conversations.

00:58:27.923 --> 00:58:30.200
And I find that
there is a deception

00:58:30.200 --> 00:58:32.490
to think that it's
just a conversation,

00:58:32.490 --> 00:58:34.550
and it's not real.

00:58:34.550 --> 00:58:37.230
So we don't realize
that we are actually

00:58:37.230 --> 00:58:42.741
part of the conversation,
and that we actually

00:58:42.741 --> 00:58:43.490
make a difference.

00:58:43.490 --> 00:58:44.994
I mean, it sounds very blase.

00:58:44.994 --> 00:58:46.160
Like, you make a difference.

00:58:46.160 --> 00:58:48.040
But it's not just speaking.

00:58:48.040 --> 00:58:50.920
It's deciding what your
posture is concerning

00:58:50.920 --> 00:58:53.030
the problem that exists.

00:58:53.030 --> 00:58:56.340
And the fact that you
may not be able to prefer

00:58:56.340 --> 00:58:59.580
a general solution
to everything.

00:58:59.580 --> 00:59:02.400
But you have a
solution for something.

00:59:02.400 --> 00:59:05.490
One of my biggest
mantras is do for one

00:59:05.490 --> 00:59:07.230
what you would do for all.

00:59:07.230 --> 00:59:11.160
And letting people realize that,
that solution that you have,

00:59:11.160 --> 00:59:13.712
that can help your
neighbor, the fact

00:59:13.712 --> 00:59:15.670
that you can share
generator with your neighbor

00:59:15.670 --> 00:59:16.924
to help him save costs.

00:59:16.924 --> 00:59:17.840
Do you not understand?

00:59:17.840 --> 00:59:21.230
Just that little tiny
solution goes a long way

00:59:21.230 --> 00:59:24.250
in you actually being
part of a conversation

00:59:24.250 --> 00:59:27.660
than tweeting at other
people and criticizing them,

00:59:27.660 --> 00:59:29.860
and telling them what
to do and how to do,

00:59:29.860 --> 00:59:33.550
is within your own parameter,
within your own boundaries.

00:59:33.550 --> 00:59:35.540
What changes can you make?

00:59:35.540 --> 00:59:37.485
And then starting
with that, I think.

00:59:37.485 --> 00:59:38.880
I think it's a small idea.

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:40.680
But I think it'll go very far.

00:59:40.680 --> 00:59:41.970
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:41.970 --> 00:59:44.050
JULIET EHUMIAN-CHIAZOR:
Thank you so much.

00:59:44.050 --> 00:59:46.240
OBY EZEKWESILI: But let
me have a final word

00:59:46.240 --> 00:59:51.020
and say to the women that are
here, and that are listening,

00:59:51.020 --> 00:59:53.690
the pressure on the
younger generation

00:59:53.690 --> 01:00:00.660
of women professionals is much
more than we even coped with.

01:00:00.660 --> 01:00:03.780
It's a world that is
much more fast paced.

01:00:03.780 --> 01:00:09.570
And the kind of expectations
that are placed on you

01:00:09.570 --> 01:00:13.050
are more varied.

01:00:13.050 --> 01:00:16.330
As a woman, one
tool that I use is

01:00:16.330 --> 01:00:18.740
what I call my five realities.

01:00:18.740 --> 01:00:22.090
My five realities
are these-- number

01:00:22.090 --> 01:00:25.470
one reality is my
reality as a human being.

01:00:25.470 --> 01:00:27.790
It is in that reality,
as a human being,

01:00:27.790 --> 01:00:32.930
that I have been given that
talent by the Almighty.

01:00:32.930 --> 01:00:35.030
That talent is unique to me.

01:00:35.030 --> 01:00:38.570
It's my authentic personality.

01:00:38.570 --> 01:00:42.220
And it is the gift that
I have, that education

01:00:42.220 --> 01:00:43.560
would have enhanced.

01:00:43.560 --> 01:00:47.750
And so in that, my reality
as a unique individual,

01:00:47.750 --> 01:00:50.680
I can be anything
that I choose to be.

01:00:50.680 --> 01:00:52.440
I can be a photographer.

01:00:52.440 --> 01:00:54.620
I can be a Google manager.

01:00:54.620 --> 01:00:57.770
I can be a radio station owner.

01:00:57.770 --> 01:00:59.170
I can be a lawyer.

01:00:59.170 --> 01:00:59.920
I can be a doctor.

01:00:59.920 --> 01:01:01.260
I can be a teacher.

01:01:01.260 --> 01:01:04.740
I can be anything
that I choose to be.

01:01:04.740 --> 01:01:10.380
And what I need is to find
what would enable maybe that.

01:01:10.380 --> 01:01:14.250
And if there be any glass
ceiling standing between me

01:01:14.250 --> 01:01:16.080
and what I can
be, I'm just going

01:01:16.080 --> 01:01:17.720
to walk through that glass.

01:01:17.720 --> 01:01:20.590
Your second reality,
my second reality,

01:01:20.590 --> 01:01:25.690
my reality as the product of
two people, a mom and a dad,

01:01:25.690 --> 01:01:28.890
they give me the
history that is mine.

01:01:28.890 --> 01:01:32.230
There would not be me
if a certain Benjamin

01:01:32.230 --> 01:01:35.120
and a certain Cecelia
did not come together.

01:01:35.120 --> 01:01:39.450
If I neglect that, my
reality, I lose my history.

01:01:39.450 --> 01:01:41.490
I lose everything
that is supposed

01:01:41.490 --> 01:01:45.210
to enable me to understand
where I have come from.

01:01:45.210 --> 01:01:48.110
So my reality as a
daughter is very important.

01:01:48.110 --> 01:01:51.830
My reality as a daughter
is what enables me to not

01:01:51.830 --> 01:01:54.910
repeat the mistakes
that my mother made,

01:01:54.910 --> 01:01:57.780
or to repeat the mistakes
that my dad made.

01:01:57.780 --> 01:02:01.440
Then my third reality is
my reality as a sibling.

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:07.610
Even if I didn't have
brothers and sisters,

01:02:07.610 --> 01:02:09.070
I must have had cousins.

01:02:09.070 --> 01:02:11.685
Because this is
Africa, after all.

01:02:11.685 --> 01:02:15.940
So that reality enables
my socialization.

01:02:15.940 --> 01:02:20.890
My reality as a sibling means
that I am a sister to a brother

01:02:20.890 --> 01:02:23.260
or to a sister, or to cousins.

01:02:23.260 --> 01:02:24.640
Now, what do they do for me?

01:02:24.640 --> 01:02:27.280
They teach me how to lead.

01:02:27.280 --> 01:02:30.210
Because in the early
days, of my growing

01:02:30.210 --> 01:02:35.550
up as a sister to brothers
and to a sister, what happened

01:02:35.550 --> 01:02:39.220
was that I needed to be
able to persuade them

01:02:39.220 --> 01:02:42.910
that it was right for us
to do this or to do that.

01:02:42.910 --> 01:02:45.420
If I didn't persuade
them, I didn't

01:02:45.420 --> 01:02:49.030
get people who followed me
to do any particular thing.

01:02:49.030 --> 01:02:54.235
I learned persuasion
by being a sister.

01:02:54.235 --> 01:03:00.430
Learned leadership by being able
to convince them to follow me.

01:03:00.430 --> 01:03:04.430
Then your fourth reality is
likely to be your reality

01:03:04.430 --> 01:03:05.770
as a wife.

01:03:05.770 --> 01:03:08.520
The companion of
this wonderful man

01:03:08.520 --> 01:03:11.602
that you decided, of all men,
that you are going to marry.

01:03:11.602 --> 01:03:15.320
I mean, that's some
incredible reality.

01:03:15.320 --> 01:03:16.690
Its partnership.

01:03:16.690 --> 01:03:19.310
Marriage teaches
you partnership.

01:03:19.310 --> 01:03:23.240
It teaches you how to not live
for yourself alone, to learn

01:03:23.240 --> 01:03:27.420
how to live for somebody
else, to sacrifice, to get

01:03:27.420 --> 01:03:31.570
to the point of intimacy
that marriage is about.

01:03:31.570 --> 01:03:36.690
